We	recommended	to management to:

Direct the City Accountant to coordinate with	various
implementing departments to identify the PPAs funded under Due	to NGAs and determine the status of implementation;

Instruct the implementing offices to prepare liquidation reports and supporting documents for fully implemented/ completed PPAs and submit them to the City Accountant;

Prepare Disbursement Vouchers for refund of the unutilized balance of the funds for return to the source agencies;

Direct City Accountant to draw journal entry vouchers to take up appropriate entries to adjust the accounts for liquidations, return of unutilized funds, and other adjustments;

Enjoin	appropriate actions to be undertaken in relation to the funds withheld related to PDAF allocations to prevent misuse or misappropriations thereof; and

Ensure monitoring of the status of funds and implementation of the PPAs; and promptly submit the liquidation reports and documents for refund of unutilized funds.

We recommended to management to:

Instruct GSO to collate all RIS related to these undispensed/non-moving inventory accounts, confirm with the requesting office/unit the issuances made to the end-users, consolidate issuances using SSMI, and forward to Accounting Office for JEV preparation;

Require the City Accountant to draw JEV to record all issuances of non-moving inventories to end-users supported with SSMIs to the appropriate expense accounts;

Enjoin the GSO to ensure submission of the SSMIs to the Accounting Office to record the issuances to appropriate expense accounts, conduct periodic physical count of inventories, and submission of the RPCIs to the Audit Team; and

Enjoin the Accounting and the GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their inventory records and prepare JEV on established balances.

We recommended to the management to:
Enjoin the City Accounting Office and the CGSO to make concerted effort to retrieve all relevant documents pertaining to the unaccounted beginning balances that may include but not limited to old records, inventory reports, and any other related documents that shall be used to reconcile and update the recorded balances;
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical inventory of all PPE that shall include all items found at station or during the inventory process, even with the absence of information in the accounting or CGSO records and shall determine the cost or value of these items or request the assistance for appraisal;
For any unreconciled or unaccounted items, file the request for authority to derecognize non-existing or missing PPEs without available records or Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs) in accordance with the requirements and procedures prescribed under Section 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
Provide disclosures in the notes to the financial statements on non-existing or missing PPEs included in the balance, classified accordingly with information on the status of any filed request for authority on derecognition.

To optimize project delivery and maximize the impact of the 20% Development Fund, we recommend the following actions for management to:
Strengthen collaboration among relevant offices and agencies as well as enhance the structured schedule of project implementation status reviews. Continuously identify and analyze causes of delays, implementing proactive remedial measures to ensure projects are attainable, adequately funded, not overlooked, and will not overlap with other agencies' projects;
Ensure the prompt implementation of priority development projects outlined in the AIP by enhancing procedures to expedite the preparation of Program of Works and the procurement process;
Furnish plan of action of all unimplemented projects, indicating whether they remain a priority or should be set aside for other immediate concerns;
Ensure utilization of any remaining unspent balances from previous years, strictly adhering to the 20% DF guidelines, to achieve the desired city-wide benefits; and
Require that all infrastructure projects under the 20% DF should be incorporated in the PPMPs for consolidation by the BAC Secretariat into the APP.

We recommended the Management to strictly adhere to the Procurement Law and its IRR, specifically by requiring concerned offices to:
Enforce the requirement for performance security to remain valid until the issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance;
Verify that all warranty securities meet the required one-year validity period from the date of final acceptance, and require the contractors to extend the securities as needed;
Ensure accurate computation of liquidated damages with proper documentation;
Comply with the provisions concerning retention money and its substitution with acceptable securities; and
Adhere to the requirement of issuing the Certificate of Final Acceptance one year after project completion, provided contractors have fulfilled all contractual obligations and posted the required warranty security.

We recommended to the management to direct the city GFPS and Technical Working Group (TWG) to:
Set the GAD agenda or identify priority gender issues to be addressed in consultation with local functionaries and stakeholders;
Capacitate the GFPS and TWG on the HGDG for proper attribution of PPAs in the preparation of the GAD budget and GAD AR;
Spearhead the institutionalization and maintenance of the GAD database per sectors that shall contain the minimum data requirements for use in the recognition of PPAs to be attributed in the GAD budget; and
Enjoin the City Budget Officer and City Accountant to establish RC codes or SL for all GAD-related expenses and PPAs.

We	recommended	to management to:
Instruct the City Accountant, City General Service Officer and the Inventory Committee to strictly adhere to the COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the guidelines and procedures for the one- time cleansing of PPE accounts balances;

Instruct the City Accountant to prepare Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC), Real Property Ledger Cards (RPLC) and Construction in Progress Ledger Cards (CPIL) for the PPE items booked in the Subsidiary Ledgers;

Instruct City General Services Officer to prepare and furnish the City Accountant the Report of Semi- Expandable Property Issued (RSPI) and the latter to make necessary journal entries for the semi-expendable properties	recorded as PPE; and

Instruct City Accountant to record the procurement of	semi-expendable properties below capitalization threshold to their appropriate inventory or expense accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2022-004.

In order to achieve the socio- economic and environmental outcomes aimed by the City Government of Oroquieta, we recommended	to management to:

Direct	the	City Engineering Office to :

Provide justification on the charging of the eight (8) ineligible expenditures in the 20% DF,

Ensure	that subsequent PPAs charged therefrom are in accordance with the provisions of DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1;

Implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe;

Direct the City Planning and Development Office to develop strategies to maximize the utilization of the 20% DF;

Direct the City General Services Office to fast- track procurement of all on-going projects under the 20% DF; and

Convene with the Local Sanggunian for the pertinent   resolutions needed to mobilize the 20% DF PPAs.

We	recommended	to the management to:

Direct the office in-charge of DRRM projects and other	personnel authorized by the management to use CDUR as basis for utilization of these cash donations;

Direct the City Accountant to record in Trust Liabilities – DRRM Subsidiary Ledgers the receipt of cash donations received amounting to ₱100,000 and above per donor per purpose while those below ₱100,000 shall be posted to “Various Donors” item;

Direct the Offices of the City Accounting and City Budget to prepare Monthly Reports of Utilization of LDRRM Fund from cash donations, submit the reports to the NDRRMC, through the OCD, copy furnish the respective COA Auditors within five (5) working days after the end of each month and forward to the Office of the City Mayor Management Information System Division for posting in the official website of the City Government; and

Direct the City Budget Office to prepare and update regularly the Registry of Cash Donations and Utilization (RCDU).

In order to ensure non- recurrence of future similar transactions and to fully establish compliance with RA No. 9184, its IRR and related GPPB issuances, we recommended	that management direct the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Provide justification on the non-attachment of the pertinent supporting documents of the contracts;

Strictly adhere to the provisions set forth in RA 9184 and its IRR;

Take note of pertinent policy and non-policy matter opinions rendered by the Government Procurement Policy Board and its Technical Support Office; and

Scrutinize the technical, legal and financial capacity of the suppliers to avoid administrative and/or criminal sanctions to be imposed upon the BAC and the suppliers.

We	recommended	to management to:

Ensure that the Projects, Programs and Activities (PPAs) outlined in the GAD plan and budget are duly reviewed and indorsed by the DILG and enforce submission through written notice to that office for any adjustments thereof;

Maximize the utilization of GAD funds through implementation of GAD- related PPAs and ensure that these are properly monitored in order to ensure that GAD goals and objectives were attained as planned;

Enjoin the Citys GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) through the City Planning and Development Office to spearhead the setting up and maintenance of a GAD Database to serve as basis for a proper and effective gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation; and

Direct the City Budget Officer and City Accountant	in coordination with the GFPS to strictly comply the assignment of separate Responsibility Center Codes or subsidiary ledger for GAD to account all GAD-related financial transactions.

We recommended to management to:

Require the City Treasurer to prepare a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which should come from the Real Property Tax Account Register or Taxpayers Index Card maintained at the City Treasurers Office and furnish the City Accountant at the beginning of the year;

Require the City Accountant to record the receivables based on the list furnished by the City Treasurer in order to record in the books pursuant to Section 20 of the NGAS Manual, Volume I;

Direct the City Treasurer to submit to the City Accountant the List of RPT Delinquencies since C.Y. 2002, as a reference of the accountants adjustment in the RPT and SET receivables;

Require the City Treasurer to ascertain the completeness of the real property units subject to tax in records. Moreover, to optimally utilize ETRACS in its real property tax transactions so that the intended benefits therefrom will be realized such as expediting data processing and improving reporting accuracy.

We recommended to management to: 

Enjoin the City GSO through the BAC to conduct the procurement of consolidated CSEs and catering services in a periodic basis per schedule;

Observe strict compliance with the implementing rules and regulations of the procurement law by adopting competitive public bidding as the primary mode of procurement;

Strictly enforce provisions of the NGAS for LGUs on the PO numbering format and ensure their issuances in chronological order for easy monitoring and control.

