We recommended to management to:

Provide justification on the acceptance of the nearly expiring vaccines contrary to the standard requirement pertaining to shelf life provided under NVOC Advisory No. 71 dated August 8, 2021;

Submit a plan of action to be taken on the procured AstraZeneca vaccines which were expired and stored within the City Office premises; 

Closely monitor the expiration dates of the COVID-19 vaccines received to prioritize the utilization of those which are near expiry to minimize wastage;

Follow the reverse logistics protocol, as mandated by the DOH, when disposing of unused vaccines and empty vials;

Enjoin the submission of the liquidation report/distribution list of the consumed, and deed of donation and Property Transfer Report (PTR) of the donated vaccines to the City Accounting Office to record the issuances to appropriate expense accounts; and
Instruct the City Accounting Office to draw JEV to record all issuances of vaccines to end-users to the appropriate expense accounts.

We recommended to management to:

Require the City Treasurer to give priority to the updating of the Certified List of Delinquent Taxpayers and designate employee/s on the regular preparation of the Tax Due Billings as the basis for collection; 

Intensify efforts to enforce collection remedies provided by Republic Act No. 7160, particularly the sale of delinquent properties through public auction to demonstrate the City’s willpower and capability to enforce the laws on real property taxation and deter tax evasions; 

Instruct the City Treasurer to revive the tax campaigns program including the regular issuance of collection letter to delinquent taxpayers indicating a grace period to update their accounts through installment payments, pursuant to Section 250 of the Local Government Code; and 

Strengthen collection of taxes on a quota basis per RCC and by barangay to have continuity of monitoring/follow-up and to reach the set collection target. Likewise, conduct more extensive tax campaigns so that taxpayers are apprised of the advantages/services the City Government renders if taxes are paid.

We recommended to management to:

Require the LDRRMC to perform its mandated functions in Section 4.1 of IRR of RA No. 10121 which includes approving, monitoring, and evaluating the implementation of the LDRRMPs and annually review, test and develop the plan consistent with other national and local planning programs;

Advise the City Planning and Development Council to ensure that the Annual Investment Plan is prepared based on the approved LDRRMFIP;

Instruct CDRMMO to submit RIS of the issuances to end-users of Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies and forward to Accounting Office for JEV preparation; and

Provide adequate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements for amount and details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF.

We recommended to management to: 

Enforce all requesting offices to prepare their respective PRs for CSEs and catering services in accordance with the schedule of purchase as indicated in their PPMPs supported with stock inventory report to stop the practice of procuring them at any time;

Enjoin the City GSO through the BAC to conduct the procurement of consolidated CSEs and catering services in a periodic basis per schedule;

Observe strict compliance with the implementing rules and regulations of the procurement law by adopting competitive public bidding as the primary mode of procurement;

Submit to COA the Purchase Orders together with their supporting documents within the reglementary period to facilitate prompt auditorial and legal review and timely inspection thereof; and

Strictly enforce provisions of the NGAS for LGUs on the PO numbering format and ensure their issuances in chronological order for easy monitoring and control.

We recommended to management to:

Closely coordinate with the Sangguniang Panlungsod to incorporate in the existing ELA the base development targets, timeframes, and measurable outcomes for legislative agenda and PPAs;

Integrate into the ELA the strategies for monitoring and evaluation;

Submit the plan of action to monitor and evaluate the implementation of the legislative agenda and PPAs identified in the ELA for CY 2023-2025; and

Submit a justification highlighting the necessity of conducting the ELA Planning outside the locality when it could have been more efficiently undertaken within the locality.

We recommended that Management reassess, restructure and tighten its internal control on the lease of heavy equipment, and ensure that provisions under City Ordinance No. 523-2013 are met.

We further recommended that Management:

a. Require the City Accountant to re-compute rent income using the approved Request Forms (from the start of leasing operations until December 31, 2019) in accordance with Sections 2 and 5 of the abovementioned ordinance and set-up the corresponding receivable account for any deficiencies noted in the declared income;

b. Require the City Treasurer to exert all efforts to collect amounts due to the government based on the recomputed income from the City Accountant’s Office. Any amount left uncollected should be charged to agency officials and/or employees responsible for the under collection;

c. Customize a Lease Contract that must be entered into by and between the lessee and the City Mayor in behalf of the City, as the lessor, for the lease of heavy equipment and forward the same to the City Auditor’s Office within the timeframe prescribed under COA Circular No. 2009-001; and

d. Make representations to the Sangguniang Panlungsod for any possible amendments to the Ordinance concerned, particularly on the computation of  rental fee, custody and release of heavy equipment, Sections 2, 5, & 9 of the Ordinance and for possible revisions of rental rates to conform with the updated ACEL Rates in order to maximize revenue therefrom.

We recommended and the management agreed the following:

a. Management acquire and provide a Biometric Machine to LGU personnel and have it installed near the different offices to register actual and prescribed office/work hours;

b. The City Mayor direct all officials and employees to register their daily attendance on the biometric machine and at the same time require the maintenance of an updated logbook per Office that should regularly be checked/inspected by the HRMO;

c. Instruct the HRMO to use only computer generated DTRs based on the captured biometric data as basis for the preparation of payrolls;

d. Further, all JOs, except those assigned in the field, be required to use the same machine or bundy clock for the establishment of a reliable number of days worked as the basis for the computation of their wages; and
e. Awaiting the Biometric Machine to be in place, the HRMO should carefully monitor and scrutinize log book entries to arrive at the correct man-hours/attendance actually rendered by LGU personnel to avoid overpayment and wastage of government funds.

